    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.25.20c-20d_0001"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Aly Collection
                    43-2</note>
                    
                <fw type="curatorial">20c</fw>
                
                <note><hi rend="double underline">Over</hi></note>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    7912 <hi rend="caps">NORTH KARLOV AVENUE
                        <lb/>
                    SKOKIE, ILLINOIS</hi>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>Oct. 8, 1957.</dateline>
    
                    <salute>Dear John:</salute></opener> <p>I read the Saturday Evening Post and today was so pleased to find a letter in it from you.</p>
                
                <p>Your mother and I corresponded for years and my mother + I loved her very much. My mother died in 1936 &#8212; and Fred and Jan are both gone &#8212; my own husband, too.</p>
                
                <p>I came here in 1949 to be near my son and his family and have adjusted myself to living here.</p>
                
                <p>Your mother was so proud of all of you and I know Grace was in Buffalo at one time. I haven't been in Wayne for some years as heart trouble keeps me <unclear>quieth</unclear> at home.</p>
                
                <p>May I wish you and yours continued happiness and I was so pleased to see your name again!!</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Most sincerely your friend,</salute>
                    <signed>Helen Pile Newton</signed>
                    <note>(Helen Pile Newton)</note>
                </closer>
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.25.20c-20d_0002"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">20d</fw>
                
                <note type="recipient">
                    <p>Helen is the daughter of Prof. <hi rend="caps">J.M.</hi> Pile who created the state college at Wayne, Nebraska. He made it possible for me to go to college by giving me the job of ringing the bell from 6:30 <hi rend="caps">A.M.</hi> to 6 <hi rend="caps">PM.</hi>, which I did for four years. Helen is the last of the family. She may be able to tell you something of the time when I was under her daddy.</p>
                    John Neihardt
                </note>
                
            </div1>
